. This is not a ‘religious’ or a ‘political’ narrative, but a synthesis of the two, paying particular attention to the international context of the Reformation, and focusing on the impact of violence - from state persecution, through terrorist activism, to open warfare. Going beyond the heroic certainties of John Knox, this book recaptures the lived experience of the early Reformation: a bewildering, dangerous and exhilarating period in which Scottish (and British) identity was remade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReformationzScotland. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aEuropean history.  aFrance.  aScottish Reformation.  amodern revolution.  anational transformations.  anationalism.  apolitics.  areligion.  areligious culture.  aviolence.1 aRyrie, Alec, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779385040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793850423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793850/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles